Currently OpenGL's `Graphics::GetMultiSampleLevels()` doesn't detect supported MSAA levels.

http://stackoverflow.com/a/9317953
and
http://nehe.gamedev.net/tutorial/fullscreen_antialiasing/16008/
suggest it's possible to detect supported level by trying to set a level, and then get it and see if you got what you originally set.
I tried it and it works, but I used `Graphics::SetMode()` which recreates the window which is ugly.

```C++
PODVector<int> Graphics::GetMultiSampleLevels()
{
	PODVector<int> ret;
	// No multisampling always supported
	ret.Push(1);

	auto original_level = multiSample_;

	// Try to set different sample levels and see if they work
	// Keep adding levels until the returned level isn't equal to the last level
	int returned_level = 1;
	int last_level = 1;
	for (int level = 2; returned_level == last_level; level *= 2)
	{
		last_level = level;

		SetMode(width_, height_, fullscreen_, borderless_, resizable_, highDPI_, vsync_, tripleBuffer_, level);
		SDL_GL_GetAttribute(SDL_GL_MULTISAMPLESAMPLES, &returned_level);

		if (returned_level == level)
			ret.Push(level);
	}

	// Restore original level
	SetMode(width_, height_, fullscreen_, borderless_, resizable_, highDPI_, vsync_, tripleBuffer_, original_level);

	return ret;
}
```

Perhaps there's a way to  set & get without re-creating the window.

In addition, `SetMode()` seems to have arbitrary max limit of 16 MSAA.
If it is arbitrary, I think it should be left to the user to decide if and how much to limit.

